                            <h1>
                            Jesus of Nazareth
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p3" class="">Elder David B. Haight</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/david-b-haight?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/david-b-haight-10.jpg" alt="David B. Haight" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            <h2>Jesus of Nazareth</h2>
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">94905_000_031</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p4" class="">I pray for a portion of your faith and prayers as I bear witness of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a>. In the hearts of all mankind, of whatever race or station in life, there are inexpressible longings for something they do not now possess. This longing is implanted by a concerned Creator.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p5" class="">A loving Heavenly Father&rsquo;s design is that this longing of the human heart should lead to the One who alone can satisfy it&mdash;even Jesus of Nazareth, who was foreordained in the Grand Council before the earth was created.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p6" class="">To the brother of Jared, the premortal Jesus said:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p7" class="">&ldquo;Behold, I am he who was prepared from the foundation of the world to redeem my people. Behold, I am <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>. &hellip; In me shall all mankind have life, and that eternally, even they who shall believe on my name&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/ether/3.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ether 3:14</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p8" class="">Today is Easter&mdash;a day designated to solemnize the bodily <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2000/05/resurrection?lang=eng">resurrection</a> of the Savior of the world. As members of His restored church, it is imperative that we do our utmost to expand our understanding of His premortal commission, His earthly ministry, His unjust crucifixion, the agony of His suffering, His final sacrifice, and His resurrection. Each of us is profoundly indebted to Him, for we were purchased by the shedding of His own precious blood. We are surely obligated to follow His admonition, to believe on His name, and to testify of Him and His word.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p9" class="">I am indebted for some of my remarks to eyewitness accounts of Christ&rsquo;s life as recorded in the New Testament; to prophets&mdash;ancient and modern&mdash;especially to the Prophet <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/joseph-smith/">Joseph Smith</a> for his personal witness that God the Father and His Son live and for his faithfully following divine instructions in bringing forth the fulness of the everlasting gospel as contained in the Book of Mormon and other latter-day scriptures; also to the apostolic writings of Elders James E. Talmage and Bruce R. McConkie; and to others, including theologian and believer Frederic Farrar. Our scriptures teach us gospel truths, and inspired writers add to our understanding.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p10" class="">We have learned that during the last days of His mortal life, Jesus had withdrawn from all public teaching and had spent the Wednesday before Passover in Bethany in seclusion. The next day, Thursday, Jesus instructed Peter and John to go to Jerusalem, where they would find a room prepared so they could meet together. In that room Jesus met with the Twelve, and they sat down to eat.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p11" class="">It was custom that as a person entered a room, he laid aside his sandals at the door and his feet were washed to remove the dust from his travels. A servant usually performed this lowly task, but on this sacred night, &ldquo;Jesus Himself, in His eternal humility and self-denial, rose from His place at the meal to do [this] menial service&rdquo; (Frederic W. Farrar, <span class="emphasis">The <a class="no-link-style" href="http://http://lds.org/manual/gospel-principles/chapter-11-the-life-of-christ?lang=eng">Life of Christ</a>,</span> Portland, Or.: Fountain Publications, 1980, p. 557).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p12" class="">Jesus said to them:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p13" class="">&ldquo;Ye call me Master and Lord: and ye say well; for so I am.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p14" class="">&ldquo;If I then, your Lord and Master, have washed your feet; ye also ought to wash one another&rsquo;s feet&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/13.13-14?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 13:13&ndash;14</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p15" class="">&ldquo;He their Lord and Master had washed their feet. It was a kind and gracious task, and such ought to be the nature of all their dealings with each other. He had done it to teach them humility, &hellip; self-denial, [and] love&rdquo; (Farrar, <span class="emphasis">Life of Christ,</span> p. 559).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p16" class="">During the course of the meal, He revealed the terrible news that one among them would betray Him, and a deep sadness fell over all of them.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p17" class="">Jesus spoke to Judas, &ldquo;That [which] thou doest, do quickly&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/13.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 13:27</a>). And Judas left the room to do his awful deed.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p18" class="">Conscious of the impending events, Jesus opened His heart to His chosen eleven, saying:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p19" class="">&ldquo;Now is the Son of man glorified, and God is glorified in him. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p20" class="">&ldquo;Little children, yet a little while I am with you. Ye shall seek me: [but] whither I go, ye cannot come. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p21" class="">&ldquo;A new commandment I give unto you, That ye love one another; as I have loved you, that ye also love one another.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p22" class="">&ldquo;By this shall all men know that ye are my disciples, if ye have love one to another&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/13.31,33-35?lang=eng#30" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 13:31, 33&ndash;35</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p23" class="">While in that upper room, Jesus&mdash;initiating the sacrament&mdash;took bread, brake it, prayed over it, and passed it to the disciples, saying, &ldquo;This is my body which is given for you: this do in remembrance of me&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/22.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 22:19</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p24" class="">And then, passing the cup, He said, &ldquo;This cup is the new testament in my blood, which is shed for you&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/22.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 22:20</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p25" class="">The Savior prayed to the Father for the Apostles and all believers, saying:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p26" class="">&ldquo;Father, the hour is come; glorify thy Son, that thy Son also may glorify thee:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p27" class="">&ldquo;As thou hast given him power over all flesh, that he should give eternal life to as many as thou hast given him.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p28" class="">&ldquo;And this is life eternal, that they might know thee the only true God, and Jesus Christ, whom thou hast sent&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/17.1-3?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 17:1&ndash;3</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p29" class="">The time which remained for Him to be with them was short. He told them of the Holy Ghost, whom He would send to comfort and guide them in truth. He taught them many things that night in the upper room as He tried to prepare them for that which He knew was coming.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p30" class="">They rose from the table, united their voices in a <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/cm/display/0,17631,4650-1,00.html">hymn</a>, and left the room together to walk to the Garden of Gethsemane and all that awaited them there.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p31" class="">&ldquo;The awful hour of His deepest [suffering] had arrived: &hellip; Nothing remained &hellip; but the torture of physical pain and &hellip; mental anguish. &hellip; He &hellip; calm[ed] His spirit by prayer and solitude to meet that hour in which all that is evil in the Power of [Satan] should wreak its worst upon the Innocent and Holy [One]. And He must face that hour alone&rdquo; (Farrar, <span class="emphasis">Life of Christ,</span> p. 575).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p32" class="">&ldquo;My soul,&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;is full of anguish, even unto death&rdquo; (ibid., p. 576). It was not the anguish and fear of pain and death but &ldquo;the burden &hellip; of the world&rsquo;s sin which lay heavy on His heart&rdquo; (ibid., p. 579).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p33" class="">&ldquo;He withdrew to find His only consolation in communing with [His Father]. And there He found all that He needed. Before that hour was over He was prepared for the worst that Satan or man could do&rdquo; (ibid., p. 580).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p34" class="">&ldquo;From the terrible conflict in Gethsemane, Christ emerged a victor. Though in the dark tribulation of that &hellip; hour He had pleaded that the bitter cup be removed from His lips, &hellip; the Father&rsquo;s will was never lost sight of&rdquo; (James E. Talmage, <span class="emphasis">Jesus the Christ,</span> Salt Lake City: Deseret Book Co., 1983, p. 569).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p35" class="">And then came Judas with his betraying kiss; Christ&rsquo;s surrender to His enemies; the arrest of the Son of God and three sham trials before the priests in the Sanhedrin; the insults and the derision of the multitudes; Christ&rsquo;s appearance before Pontius Pilate, then Herod, then again before Pilate. Then came the final pronouncement of Pilate. After three appeals to the multitude of Jews to spare one of their own fell upon deaf ears, he delivered Jesus to be scourged.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p36" class="">&ldquo;Scourging was the ordinary preliminary to crucifixion. &hellip; The &hellip; sufferer was publicly stripped, &hellip; tied &hellip; to a pillar, and then &hellip; blows were inflicted with leathern thongs, weighted with jagged &hellip; bone [or rock]. &hellip; The victim generally fainted, [or] often died&rdquo; (Farrar, <span class="emphasis">Life of Christ,</span> p. 624).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p37" class="">When the cross had been prepared, they placed it upon His shoulders and led Him to Golgotha. &ldquo;But Jesus was enfeebled &hellip; by [hours] of violent &hellip; agitation, &hellip; by an evening of deep &hellip; emotion, &hellip; by the mental [anguish] of the garden, [and] by [the] three trials and three sentences of death before the Jews. &hellip; All [of] these, [added] to the [wounds] of the scourging [and loss of blood], had utterly broken &hellip; His physical strength&rdquo; (ibid., pp. 634&ndash;35). So a bystander was enlisted to carry the heavy cross.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p38" class="">At Calvary, Christ was laid down upon the cross. &ldquo;His arms were stretched along the cross-beams; and at the centre of the open palms, the point of a huge iron nail was placed, &hellip; [and] driven &hellip; [through the quivering flesh] into the wood&rdquo; (ibid., p. 639). His feet were also nailed to the cross, which was slowly raised and fixed firmly in the ground. &ldquo;<span class="emphasis">All</span> the voices about Him rang with blasphemy and spite, and in that long slow agony His dying ear caught no [words] of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/topic/gratitude/">gratitude</a>, of pity, or of love&rdquo; (ibid., p. 644). Every movement would be agony to the fresh wounds in the hands and the feet. &ldquo;Dizziness, &hellip; thirst, &hellip; sleeplessness, &hellip; fever, &hellip; long [hours] of torment. &hellip; Such was the death to which Christ was doomed&rdquo; (ibid., p. 641).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p39" class="">Jesus was nailed to the cross on that fateful Friday morning, probably between nine and ten o&rsquo;clock. &ldquo;At noontide the light of the sun was obscured, and black darkness spread over the whole land. The terrifying gloom continued for a period of three hours. &hellip; It was a fitting sign of the earth&rsquo;s deep mourning over the impending death of her Creator&rdquo; (Talmage, <span class="emphasis">Jesus the Christ,</span> pp. 612&ndash;13).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p40" class="">At the ninth hour Christ uttered that anguished cry, &ldquo;&lsquo;My God, my God, why hast thou forsaken me?&rsquo;&rdquo; [<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/27.46?lang=eng#45" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 27:46</a>] &ldquo;In that bitterest hour the dying Christ was alone. [So] that the supreme sacrifice of the Son might be consummated in all its fulness, the Father seems to have withdrawn &hellip; His immediate Presence, leaving to the Savior of men the glory of complete victory over the forces of sin and death&rdquo; (ibid., p. 661).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p41" class="">Later, &ldquo;realizing that He was no longer forsaken, but that His atoning sacrifice had been accepted by the Father, and that His mission in the flesh had been carried to glorious consummation, He exclaimed in a loud voice of holy triumph: <span class="emphasis">&lsquo;It is finished.&rsquo;</span> In reverence, resignation, and relief, He addressed the Father saying: <span class="emphasis">&lsquo;Father, into thy hands I commend my spirit.&rsquo;</span> He bowed His head, and voluntarily gave up His life&rdquo; (ibid., p. 615).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p42" class="">&ldquo;At that moment the vail of the Temple was rent in twain from the top to the bottom. An earthquake shook the earth. &hellip; The multitude, [now] utterly sobered, &hellip; returned to Jerusalem&rdquo; (Farrar, <span class="emphasis">Life of Christ,</span> pp. 651&ndash;52).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p43" class="">Christ&rsquo;s body was lovingly taken from the cross, placed on fine linen purchased by Joseph of Arimathea, covered with rich spices, and carried to a nearby garden where a new tomb belonging to Joseph was located.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p44" class="">It was now late in the afternoon, and &ldquo;the preparations had to be hurried, because when the sun had set the Sabbath would have begun. All that they could do, therefore, was to wash [and lay the precious body] amid the spices, to wrap the head in a white napkin, to roll the fine linen round &hellip; the wounded limbs, and to lay the body reverently in the rocky niche&rdquo; (ibid., p. 659). Then a great stone was rolled across the opening of the tomb.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p45" class="">On the dawn of that first-ever Easter morn, the two Marys, along with other women, carried their precious spices and ointments to the tomb to finish preparing the body. They wondered who would help them remove the stone from the opening of the sepulchre. To their amazement, they found the heavy stone already rolled away, the body of Jesus gone, and two angels in white bearing witness that Christ had risen from the dead. The two women hurried to the disciples with their news. John and Peter rushed to the tomb to find that it was so. The grave was empty.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p46" class="">Mary of Magdala returned once more to the tomb and there uttered the words, &ldquo;They have taken away my Lord, and I know not where they have laid him&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/20.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 20:13</a>). And then Jesus Himself stood before her and said to her, &ldquo;Mary&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/20.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 20:16</a>). Now that she recognized Him, He gently instructed her, &ldquo;Touch me not; for I [have] not yet ascended to my Father: but go to my brethren, and say unto them, I ascend unto my Father, and your Father; and to my God, and your God&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/20.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 20:17</a>). And she hastened to obey.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p47" class="">After rising from the tomb on the third day after His crucifixion, Jesus appeared not only to Mary but to the other women also. A third appearance of Jesus was to Peter. On the same day, two of the disciples were on their way to the village named Emmaus when Christ joined with them. Once more, for the fifth time on that memorable Easter day, Jesus manifested Himself to His disciples. Ten of them were gathered together seeking solace when Christ appeared before them.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p48" class="">&ldquo;Peace be unto you,&rdquo; He said.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p49" class="">&ldquo;Behold my hands and my feet, that it is I myself: handle me, and see; for a spirit hath not flesh and bones, as ye see me have&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/24.36,39?lang=eng#35" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 24:36, 39</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p50" class="">Later on, at the seashore at Galilee, while the Savior and the disciples were eating fish together, Jesus asked Peter, &ldquo;Simon, son of Jonas, lovest thou me more than these?&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p51" class="">&ldquo;Yea, Lord; thou knowest that I love thee.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p52" class="">&ldquo;Feed my lambs.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p53" class="">&ldquo;Simon, son of Jonas, lovest thou me?&rdquo; He asked again.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p54" class="">&ldquo;Yea, Lord; thou knowest that I love thee.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p55" class="">&ldquo;Feed my sheep.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p56" class="">A third time: &ldquo;Simon, son of Jonas, lovest thou me?&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p57" class="">In anguish, Peter said, &ldquo;Lord, thou knowest all things; thou knowest that I love thee.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p58" class="">And the Savior replied yet again, &ldquo;Feed my sheep&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/21.15-17?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 21:15&ndash;17</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p59" class="">As the place of His ascension, Jesus chose the Mount of Olives. Here on the Mount the Savior instructed the Apostles and those whom He had commissioned:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p60" class="">&ldquo;Go ye therefore, and teach all nations, <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/study/topics/baptism?lang=eng">baptizing</a> them in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Ghost:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p61" class="">&ldquo;Teaching them to observe all things whatsoever I have commanded you: and, lo, I am with you alway, even unto the end of the world&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/28.19-20?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 28:19&ndash;20</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p62" class="">This is our mandate. This is why we go to all nations of the earth proclaiming His gospel.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p63" class="">Eliza R. Snow, who loved this work&mdash;as do I&mdash;wrote these precious lines:</p>
			<div class="figure">
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">How great the wisdom and the love</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">That filled the courts on high</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">And sent the Savior from above</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">To suffer, bleed, and die!</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">His precious blood he freely spilt;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">His life he freely gave,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">A sinless sacrifice for guilt,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">A dying world to save. &hellip;</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">How great, how glorious, how complete,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Redemption&rsquo;s grand design,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Where justice, love, and mercy meet</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">In harmony divine!</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="citationInfo" id="">
					<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p76" class="">(<span class="emphasis">Hymns,</span> 1985, no. 195)</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1994/05/jesus-of-nazareth.p77" class="">The prophet Alma taught that the plan of mercy required an atonement to be made by God himself &ldquo;to appease the demands of justice,&rdquo; that God might be a perfect, just, and merciful God (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/42.15?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 42:15</a>). I bear witness that He lives, that He is our Savior. His is the pathway to true happiness, I declare in His holy name, Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
